ricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUsing welfare as a prism, Religion and Welfare in Europe explores regional conceptions and variations in welfare and religion across Europe. Methodological approaches to research and practice draw thematic comparisons on these issues using case studies focused on gendered and minority perspectives as they relate to the varied provision of social welfare in selected European countries. Contributors offer comparative insights on majority-minority relations concerning practices, patterns and mechanisms of social welfare provision, explaining how these lead to conflict, cohesion or – as is so often the case – the grey area in between. The book will be of interest not only to religion and social policy researchers, but to welfare practitioners and policy advisors with a particular interest in the interaction between religion, social welfare, minorities and gender.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChurch and social problemszEuropevCross-cultural studies. 0aPublic welfarezEuropevCross-cultural studies. 0aPublic welfarezEuropexReligious aspects. 0aReligion and sociologyzEurope. 0aWelfare statezEurope. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh1 aAngell, Olav Helge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBäckström, Anders, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavie, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFokas, Effie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrisina, Annalisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaiho, Marjukka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeis-Peters, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/